<TITLE> At least four killed in Cameroon port city violence </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 DOUALA, Cameroon, Feb 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - At least four people were killed when violence and looting broke out in Cameroon's economic capital Douala on Monday after taxi drivers launched a strike against high fuel prices, police and witnesses said. "Two persons were pulled out of their car and beaten to death at Bonaberi neighbourhood. One man was burned to death when the Douala Five Council was set ablaze and another young man suffocated after inhaling too much tear gas," a police officer in Douala, who asked not to be named, told Reuters. Witnesses said police were firing into the air and firing tear gas to try to disperse groups of protesters and looters around the city, one of West Africa's major ports which also ships cocoa from the world's fourth biggest producer. The striking taxi drivers set fire to car tyres and put up barricades across streets and roads, paralysing traffic, the witnesses said. Petrol stations were looted. Monday's violence followed a clash in Douala on Saturday between police and opposition supporters protesting against a plan by President Paul Biya to extend his 25-year rule in Cameroon. At least one protester was shot dead on Saturd
